Background

A lot of the information here (especially the NZ-specific stuff) was extracted from the posts by Peter Ellis on Rbloggers:

  • https://www.r-bloggers.com/election-analysis-contest-entry-part-1-introducing-the-nzelect-r-package/
  • https://www.r-bloggers.com/election-analysis-contest-entry-part-2-building-the-nzelect-r-package/
  • https://www.r-bloggers.com/election-analysis-contest-entry-part-3-interactive-exploration-of-voting-locations-with-leaflet-and-shiny/
  • https://www.r-bloggers.com/election-analysis-contest-entry-part-4-drivers-of-preference-for-green-over-labour-party/
  • https://www.r-bloggers.com/nzelect-0-2-0-on-cran/

which relate to his R package nzelect, which displays NZ election results by electorate:

  • https://github.com/ellisp/nzelect

You can either install this in R from CRAN via:

install.packages('nzelect')

or directly from GitHub using devtools via:

# install the nzcensus package (note it is part of the nzelect GitHub repository):
devtools::install_github("ellisp/nzelect/pkg1")

Also available is the nzcensus package, which might be even more useful

  • https://www.r-bloggers.com/nzcensus-on-github/

Note that this is part of the nzelect github repo (see link above), and can be installed via:

# install the nzcensus package (note it is part of the nzelect GitHub repository):
devtools::install_github("ellisp/nzelect/pkg2")

NZ map data from Statistics NZ

Bulleted text below is from the following website:

http://www.stats.govt.nz/browse_for_stats/Maps_and_geography.aspx

  • Geographic areas - find a variety of geographic information, including definitions. Find data, reports, and maps of New Zealand and subnational areas: http://www.stats.govt.nz/browse_for_stats/Maps_and_geography/Geographic-areas.aspx

  • Geographic boundary files - download shapefiles, geodatabases, and MapInfo files to use within GIS software. The geographic boundary files contain statistical and administrative geographic boundaries for New Zealand, including general and Mori electoral districts. Also find metadata for the geographic boundaries. http://www.stats.govt.nz/browse_for_stats/Maps_and_geography/Geographic-areas/digital-boundary-files.aspx

There is an old (~2008) PDF explaining some of this stuff at:

http://www3.stats.govt.nz/digitalboundaries/census/NZ%20Digital%20Boundaries%20Metadata_2008.pdf

In Peters package, he used the following map data (see the file prep/download_map_shapefiles.R in the nzelect github repo):

http://www3.stats.govt.nz/digitalboundaries/annual/ESRI_Shapefile_Digital_Boundaries_2014_Generalised_12_Mile.zip

NB: the 12_Mile vs clipped representation relates to whether or not the 12 mile (ocean) limit is included as part of the map, or whether the mapped is clipped to the shoreline.

Within the directory that is created when the file unzipped, the .shp files are the shapefiles containing the various boundaries. These include:

http://www.stats.govt.nz/browse_for_stats/Maps_and_geography/Geographic-areas/geographic-area-files.aspx

Code Description
REGC Regional council
TASUB Territorial authority (???) subunit
CON Regional council constituency
WARD Ward
TA Territorial authority
MCON Maori constiuency
CB Community board
AU Census area unit
UA Urban area
MB Meshblock

Other relevant codes (that can apparently be created from meshblock data) are:

Code Description
DHB_code District health board code
DHBCON_code District health board constituency code
HDOM2006_code Health domicile 2006 code

How these things fit together as a geographic hieracrhcy can be seen here:

http://www.stats.govt.nz/methods/classifications-and-standards/geographic-hierarchy.aspx

NZ data

Smallest unit is the meshblock - these can be combined together to generate other larger units (e.g., census blocks or District Health Boards).

NZ Cancer Registry data

The NZCR provides location data in terms of domiciles, which relate to

Domicile code data (V3 2013):

http://www.health.govt.nz/nz-health-statistics/data-references/code-tables/common-code-tables/domicile-code-table

This file maps domicile codes to TLA (???) 2013 census area units (AU-13), DHB code and RHA reg (???). The diversity example above uses census area units to aggregate and plot the ethnicity data, so it should be possible to use this info to plot things by DHB. Just need to figure out how to combine census area units for plotting.

DHB shapefile

A DHB shapefile is available from:

https://koordinates.com/layer/4324-nz-district-health-boards-2012/

I have downloaded this file (had to create an account), but need to remember that it has a CC attribution license:

  • Creative Commons Attribution 3.0 New Zealand
    • You may use this work for commercial purposes.
    • You must attribute the creator in your own works.
  • Creator is Ministry of Health
## Load the rgeos and rgdal libraries to allow reading and simplifying of the shapefile
library(rgeos)
library(rgdal)

## I don't think that these were used...
## Actually maptools is needs - see below
## library(maptools)
## library(shapefiles)

## Read in the DHB shapefile and count the number of polygons
area <- readOGR(dsn="nz-dhb/",layer="nz-district-health-boards-2012")
## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: "nz-dhb/", layer: "nz-district-health-boards-2012"
## with 20 features
## It has 2 fields
## Warning in readOGR(dsn = "nz-dhb/", layer = "nz-district-health-
## boards-2012"): Z-dimension discarded
sum(unlist(lapply(area@polygons, function(x) nrow(x@Polygons[[1]]@coords))))
## [1] 240461
## DHB info (useful for determining plotting order)
dim(area@data)
## [1] 20  2
head(area@data)
##   DHB12               NAME
## 0     6              Lakes
## 1    10        Hawke's Bay
## 2     3           Auckland
## 3    18         Canterbury
## 4     2          Waitemata
## 5    16 Nelson Marlborough
## Create new object for simplified polygons
areax <- area
## Replace the polygon data with simplified data ("tol" controls amoutn of simplification)
## NB - gSimplify doesn't preserve the area@data slot, so this is a 
##      kludge to keep the same object class
## Tolerance of 1000 still gives a very good representation (10,000 starts looking ugly)
tolerance <- 1000
areax@polygons <- gSimplify(area, tol=tolerance, topologyPreserve=TRUE)@polygons
getClass(class(area))
## Class "SpatialPolygonsDataFrame" [package "sp"]
## 
## Slots:
##                                                                   
## Name:         data    polygons   plotOrder        bbox proj4string

## 
## Extends: 
## Class "SpatialPolygons", directly
## Class "Spatial", by class "SpatialPolygons", distance 2
## Class "SpatialPolygonsNULL", by class "SpatialPolygons", distance 2, with explicit coerce
getClass(class(gSimplify(area, tol=tolerance, topologyPreserve=TRUE)))
## Class "SpatialPolygons" [package "sp"]
## 
## Slots:
##                                                       
## Name:     polygons   plotOrder        bbox proj4string
## Class:        list     integer      matrix         CRS
## 
## Extends: "Spatial", "SpatialPolygonsNULL"
## 
## Known Subclasses: 
## Class "SpatialPolygonsDataFrame", directly, with explicit coerce
## How many polygons do we have now?
sum(unlist(lapply(areax@polygons, function(x) nrow(x@Polygons[[1]]@coords))))
## [1] 5927
## Base R plot of simplified data (actually looks okay)
plot(areax, col=1:20)

We can also use ggplot to plot the data, using Hadleys approach from:

https://github.com/tidyverse/ggplot2/wiki/plotting-polygon-shapefiles

To get this to run in Rmarkdown, I had to modify the instrutcions slightly to replace the fortify function with the tidy function from the broom package (although the code worked fine from the R console - actually this was due to having the maptools package loaded, see below). Using broom was based on the future decrepation message on the fortify help page.
Info about using tidy came from:

http://stackoverflow.com/questions/34543468/successor-to-ggplot2fortify

Actually, the solution is simply to load the maptools package:

https://github.com/tidyverse/ggplot2/issues/1447

Once this is done, both ggplot2::fortify and `broom::tidy`` work just fine.

Plotting takes slightly longer than base R

library(ggplot2)
library(plyr)
library(maptools)
library(broom)
areax@data$id = rownames(areax@data)
areax.points = tidy(areax, region="id")
areax.df = join(areax.points, areax@data, by="id")
dim(areax.df)
## [1] 30341     9

Installation notes

The R package rgdal provides an interface to the GDAL software (Geospatial Data Abstraction Library) for working with geospatial data.

I download the current version of GDAL:

wget http://download.osgeo.org/gdal/CURRENT/gdal-2.1.2.tar.gz

and then compiled from source via the usual:

./configure
make
make install

which installed it to /usr/local/bin.

The rgdal package could then be installed in R via:

install.packages(rgdal)
library(rgdal)
